\subsection{Settings}
\paragraph{Datasets.}
Since no publicly available LaTeX document dataset currently exists, we constructed our test set by selecting the TeX sources of 50 English academic papers from the arXiv repository. The chosen papers include both long and short articles, many of which contain complex formulas and figures, ensuring structural diversity and complexity in the LaTeX content.
Further experimental details are provided in Appendix~\ref{app:detailed-settings}.

\paragraph{Baselines.}
Our baselines are categorized into two groups: traditional MT systems and LLM-based translation systems. For the former, we selected NiuTrans and Google Translate as representative systems. For the latter, we evaluated five strong LLMs, including both open-source and proprietary models: LLaMA-3.1-8B \cite{grattafiori2024llama}, Qwen-3-8B \cite{yang2025qwen3}, Qwen-3-14B, DeepSeek-V3 \cite{liu2024deepseek}, and GPT-4o \cite{hurst2024gpt}. Among these, Qwen-3-14B, DeepSeek-V3, and GPT-4o were further used as the backbone models for agents in LaTeXTrans.

